In response to Rob's Thursday, Nov 28, posting on Guilt:<br><br>
A lot of &quot;non-combat&quot; GIs serving in Nam felt survivor guilt and that was one reason why some GIs volunteered for combat duty.  I arrived and was &quot;processed&quot; in-country with two guys who, like me, were were given &quot;safe&quot; duty assignments at a medium sized base camp.  Both of these volunteered for front-line action because they felt bored, wanted more excitement, felt guilty, etc.<br><br>
Both of them were very lucky - they can came back and the three of us left Nam on the same plane.  But both were wounded mentally in some way and neither wanted to go through what they experienced again.  And I had lots of friends who were grunts or door-gunners that extended their duty tours to get out of combat assignments.  When I talked to them about my feelings of guilt about being in a &quot;safe&quot; base camp, to a man, they all said that anyone who &quot;felt guilty&quot; about not being sent out into the jungle as cannon fodder was either crazy or just plain dumb.  <br><br>
Do you want an explanation why you feel guilty?  Why does one guy jump on a land mine or grenade and sacrifice himself to save other guys in their squad?  It's the same thing, man. Sometimes its just hard to sit by and watch as people are dying when you're safe.  You get an urge to go out and help, and if you don't or can't, you feel like you have let them down somehow. <br><br>
Man, don't feel guilty about not having served.  But if you still feel quilty, you can do something now by volunteering some of your time to help some of the more unfortunate Vets who didn't get through the Nam in one piece.<br><br>
Peace.
